{"type":"message","id":"5ee9e4fd","parentId":"cf7a7d9e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:22:21.192Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I found it. There's a file `memory/2026-03-24-training-aggression-tune.md` that mentions SRMoE and was from a conversation on March 23rd. Let me read that file to understand what we were doing with SRMoE.","thinkingSignature":"30cb8b46dffc5ddf6b43fd173c393a83b775ead72ef64f83994e48648fc5ae41"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hh1sqwtkeyzp_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-24-training-aggression-tune.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":10577,"output":105,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24857,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774354937341}}
{"type":"message","id":"ea362329","parentId":"5ee9e4fd","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:22:21.286Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hh1sqwtkeyzp_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Session: 2026-03-24 01:33:54 UTC\n\n- **Session Key**: agent:main:telegram:direct:8371302588\n- **Session ID**: b4ac2537-b0a2-44af-9e35-5cb59f389309\n- **Source**: telegram\n\n## Conversation Summary\n\nassistant: ✅ New session started · model: minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7\nuser: A new session was started via /new or /reset. Run your Session Startup sequence - read the required files before responding to the user. Then greet the user in your configured persona, if one is provided. Be yourself - use your defined voice, mannerisms, and mood. Keep it to 1-3 sentences and ask what they want to do. If the runtime model differs from default_model in the system prompt, mention the default model. Do not mention internal steps, files, tools, or reasoning.\nCurrent time: Monday, March 23rd, 2026 — 7:52 PM (America/New_York) / 2026-03-23 23:52 UTC\nassistant: Hey Zach — ready to go. What's the plan for tonight?\nuser: Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"634\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-23 19:54 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nPhase 1: Supervised pre-training (2000 ep)\n ep 0: loss=5.0961 acc=0.000 route_ce=1.0792 div=0.0602\n ep 200: loss=5.0577 acc=0.000 route_ce=1.0796 div=0.0622\n ep 400: loss=4.9727 acc=0.050 route_ce=1.0562 div=0.0624\n ep 600: loss=4.9908 acc=0.050 route_ce=1.0550 div=0.0624 it the training to agressive?\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Ep 600 and acc=0.050 is basically random for a routing task — not great, but you're only 30% through the schedule. A few thoughts:\n\n**Could go more aggressive if:**\n- The architecture supports it and this is just slow convergence\n- Learning rate is on the conservative side\n- The task is genuinely hard and you want faster signal\n\n**Could also be:**\n- Loss is actually dropping (5.096 → 4.972) — there IS learning, just slow\n- Route CE (1.05) is reasonably low — routing decisions might be learning while the main task head is lagging\n- Early epochs on a hard task sometimes need a burn-in period\n\n**What would \"more aggressive\" mean for you?** Higher LR? More weight on the main task head vs routing loss? Shorter schedule with bigger steps?\n\nAlso — what's the architecture和数据? If it's a fresh init, 2000 epochs might just be the right amount and this is normal. If it's a retrain of something that was working, then acc=0.050 at ep 600 is a red flag worth debugging before pushing harder.\nuser: Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"637\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-23 19:54 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nno its srmoe\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Got it, SRMoE — that makes more sense.\n\n**Low div=0.06 is the immediate red flag.** That's near zero, meaning your router is collapsing — likely routing almost everything to 1-2 experts instead of distributing across the mixture. When the router collapses, the other experts never get trained, so acc stays at random.\n\n**What to check:**\n\n1. **Router architecture** — is it a simple linear layer or something with enough capacity to differentiate? A single linear layer with softmax on 8-16 experts can easily collapse.\n\n2. **Load balancing loss weight** — if you're using an auxiliary load balancing loss, how heavy is it? At 0.06 divergence you're basically not enforcing it hard enough.\n\n3. **Expert capacity** — are some experts just better (or more accessible) than others at initialization? If one expert gets lucky early and receives most signal, it compounds.\n\n4. **Input preprocessing** — are tokens being routed based on meaningful features or noise? If the routing signal at the token level is weak, the router can't learn.\n\n**Quick diagnostic to add:** Log the actual expert selection distribution per epoch. If it goes [0.9, 0.05, 0.03, 0.01, ...] by ep 200, you have collapse. If it's more uniform like [0.3, 0.25, 0.2, 0.15, 0.1], you're fine.\n\nWhat's your expert count and router architecture?\nuser: Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"640\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-23 19:55 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\ni dont know lol\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Let me find it.\n\nassistant: [[reply_to_current]] Found it — this is HGSEL (hash-based sparse expert layer), not a learned router. That's an important distinction.\n\n**The architecture:**\n- Router: `MultiHashRouter` — deterministic hash of quantized hidden states (sign + magnitude buckets). No learned weights.\n- `n_experts=64`, `k_active=2`, `n_hashes=4` (likely defaults)\n- Salt parameter is the only load-balancing knob — it's set once and NOT tuned during training\n\n**Why div=0.06 is probably fine:**\n\n`div` is likely the **utilization entropy** normalized by max entropy. With a deterministic hash router, divergence near 0.06 at epoch 200 makes sense — the hash routing is fixed at initialization and doesn't improve with training. The salt is your only lever, and it sounds like it hasn't been tuned yet.\n\nThe good news: **this is Phase 1 (pre-training, 2000 epochs).** The goal is to warm up the experts, not optimize routing. The hash router will naturally sample ~`n_hashes choose k_active` = 6 unique expert combinations per token — that's the design.\n\n**What \"more aggressive\" actually means here:**\n\nSince there's no learned router to make more aggressive, you'd be aggressive on:\n1. **Salt tuning** — run a quick hill climb to find a salt that maximizes utilization entropy\n2. **More hashes** (if `n_hashes` is low) — more candidate hashes = more unique expert combos available\n3. **Lower `k_active`** — fewer experts selected = sparser, more specialized routing\n4. **Increase utilization loss weight** — push harder on the auxiliary loss if it's too low to affect training\n\n**Quick diagnostic to add right now:**\n```python\n# In your training loop — print the actual expert load distribution:\nprint(layer.expert_load_ema)  # Should be ~1/64 = 0.0156 each if uniform\n```\n\nIf one expert has 0.9 and the rest are near 0, you have collapse. If they're all within 2x of each other, the hash router is working as designed and div=0.06 is just the entropy ceiling for this deterministic system.\n\nWhat does `n_experts`, `n_hashes`, and the current salt value look like in your config?\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774354941240}}
