{"type":"message","id":"8c8e17f9","parentId":"006128e0","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:24:39.093Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the context. Let me address both questions:\n\n1. **SRMoE notebook** - Located at `C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb`. It's running on a Quadro RTX 5000 (GPU). The training has 3 phases:\n   - Phase 1: Supervised pre-training (2000 epochs) - COMPLETED with acc=0.850 at ep 1999\n   - Phase 2: Imitation learning (5000 epochs) - STARTED but at ep 1000 it crashed (acc=0.000, route_ce still ~1.05, wr=0.29, rd=0.00, skip=0.71, blkd=0.71)\n   - Phase 3: Hardening (2000 epochs) - NOT STARTED\n\nThe concerning pattern in Phase 2 is that the model starts mimicking the oracle routing but then diverges. At ep 500, it shows write rate=0.29 (oracle-like behavior emerging), but by ep 1000 it's hitting 0.000 accuracy with a blocked rate of 0.71 - meaning 71% of routing decisions are being blocked by the budget constraint. This suggests the routing policy learned during Phase 1 is generating actions that exceed the budget limits in Phase 2, causing the episode to terminate before producing valid outputs.\n\n2. **Experiment 13** - The production trace replay experiment. It showed:\n   - 65.1% P99 latency improvement (expected 54.3%, so 20% synergy over expected)\n   - SLA compliance: 81.2% → 98.2%\n   - P50 latency improvement: 80%\n   - 90.4% of tail latency incidents prevented\n   - 3/5 success criteria passed (incident prevention was 90.4% vs 94% required)\n   - The synergy was that experiment 13 combined with others (7, 9, 11) gave better results than the sum of parts\n\nThe Phase 2 collapse is puzzling - I'm seeing zero accuracy despite the routing decisions themselves looking reasonable (write=0.29, skip=0.71, blocked=0.71). The accuracy metric only measures answer correctness during query steps, so the zero suggests the model is either not reaching query steps or is producing wrong answers there. The blocked rate being so high is suspicious - it might be preventing the model from ever properly learning the query-answer association during imitation learning.\n\nIf the routing policy keeps getting blocked (71% of the time), then the episode might be terminating early before the model can practice query-answer mappings. The fix in the code was to transition from oracle routing to learned routing over 300 steps, but if the learned policy immediately produces high blockage rates, it would short-circuit the imitation learning before it can benefit from the query phase practice.","thinkingSignature":"35394021fb8f39fa58388443f00a1ee2ee667fdfa9e6f76f2550a551a6c63737"},{"type":"text","text":"OK — two things:\n\n**SRMoE notebook** (`C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb`) is on your RTX 5000. Training is through Phase 1 (acc=0.850 ✓) but **Phase 2 is collapsing** — it hit ep 1000 with acc=0.000 and blkd=0.71 (71% of routing decisions blocked by budget). That's the problem: the learned routing is firing WRITE too aggressively during imitation learning, exhausting the budget before the query phase even runs. The model never gets to practice the answer head.\n\nQuick fix options:\n1. **Lower `budget_B`** — currently 55, maybe too loose for learned routing\n2. **Increase `lambda_margin`** — push harder on margin loss so WRITE only fires when it's clearly warranted\n3. **Tune the imitation transition** — FIX #3 already does gradual transition (oracle → learned over 300 eps), but maybe the learned policy needs more burn-in before being trusted\n4. **Oracle for query steps too** — force oracle routing during the query phase so the answer head gets trained even if routing is still bad\n\n**Experiment 13** — the production trace replay. 65.1% P99 latency improvement (expected 54.3%, so 20% synergy bonus over linear prediction). SLA compliance jumped 81.2% → 98.2%. The interesting finding: when combined with exp 7+9+13, the compound effect on latency was 65% vs 54% expected — the techniques synergize, not just add. Ready for real production validation.\n\nWhat's the plan — debug Phase 2 collapse first, or push forward to Phase 3 hardening?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":72935,"output":947,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":88057,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774355050184}}
{"type":"message","id":"c4e0ad0f","parentId":"8c8e17f9","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:29:47.938Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"390\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 08:29 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nwould the dual heads help?"}],"timestamp":1774355387927}}
{"type":"message","id":"454034a5","parentId":"c4e0ad0f","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:30:58.073Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking whether the dual-head approach (similar to infant) would help with the SRMoE Phase 2 collapse problem. Let me think about this.\n\nIn the `infant` project (which I know about from memory), the dual-head architecture is key - it has separate heads for different tasks that prevent catastrophic forgetting. The idea is that instead of a single shared head that tries to do everything, you have specialized heads that learn independently.\n\nIn SRMoE's case, the problem is:\n- The routing head is learning to route (SKIP/READ/WRITE)\n- The answer head is learning to predict values\n- During Phase 2 (imitation learning), the routing head is being trained with oracle actions, but it's also being asked to learn from the answer loss indirectly\n\n\n- Actually, I need to look more carefully at the loss function - it's combining the answer loss with weighted routing and margin losses. The real bottleneck seems to be that the routing decisions themselves are consuming the budget too quickly, which then prevents the answer head from getting the signal it needs to learn effectively.\n\nThe dual-head approach would actually make this worse, not better. In infant, the whole point is that each head has its own dedicated parameters that never get overwritten - so the routing head would specialize and lock in its expertise, and the answer head would do the same. But here, if I split them further, the routing head would still be competing for the same limited budget, and now I have two heads that each need to learn independently without interfering with each other. The budget exhaustion happens because the router isn't learning to respect constraints properly - it fires actions even when the budget is depleted. A separate answer head wouldn't directly solve this; it would just isolate the prediction task from routing decisions.\n\nWhat might actually help is decoupling the routing policy from the budget state entirely - instead of feeding budget_remaining into the routing decisions, the router could learn based purely on token semantics, with a separate critic mechanism enforcing budget constraints. The infant paper's dual-head design keeps prediction and generation separated so they don't compete for capacity, which is different from SRMoE's routing problem where the core issue is that the router keeps making expensive decisions even when the budget is exhausted.\n\nLet me look more carefully at how the budget is actually being enforced in the forward pass - the action gets selected first, then budget.step() is called to check if it's permitted, and if not, it gets forced to SKIP. So the issue is that the router is selecting actions without knowing whether they're actually allowed, creating a mismatch between what it learns to do and what it can actually do. The issue is that during imitation learning, the router keeps producing WRITE actions even when the budget runs out, causing 71% of steps to get blocked. Rather than decoupling the heads, the problem seems to be that the router isn't properly accounting for budget availability when making routing decisions. The margin loss should be helping by pushing WRITE logits above SKIP logits, but it appears to have collapsed entirely—margin=0.0000 at ep 1000 suggests the model is no longer learning to distinguish between these actions. The real fix is likely adjusting the budget parameter itself rather than fundamentally changing the architecture.\n\nBut Zach's actual question is about whether a dual-head setup like infant would help here. The answer depends on what infant's dual-head actually does: if it separates routing from value prediction into independent heads, that could prevent the answer head from being starved when the routing head consumes all the gradient. Alternatively, if it uses separate heads for encoding versus query phases, that would ensure the answer head gets trained during query steps regardless of what the routing head decides. The key insight is that gradient starvation—where one head's updates interfere with another's—might be what's happening here.\n\nLooking at the code, the answer head only receives gradient during query steps (150-190), while the routing head gets gradient across all steps. This creates a severe imbalance in update frequency, and since the final loss combines both heads' contributions, the routing loss could dominate and destabilize the answer head's learning. The margin loss should theoretically enforce that WRITE actions produce stronger logits than SKIP actions, but if it's collapsing, the model might not be respecting that constraint during the imitation phase.\n\nThe core issue seems to be that the routing head is learning to route correctly in isolation, but when combined with the margin constraint, the WRITE actions are being blocked too frequently by the budget, which starves the answer head of the signal it needs to learn the actual answer values. I'm realizing that in SRMoE, the routing and answer predictions are actually separate outputs—the router produces action_logits while the main model produces answer logits, so they're not in direct competition for the same output pathway.\n\nThe real issue seems to be that the router keeps generating WRITE actions even when the budget is depleted, which blocks the answer head from ever being trained on those steps. A dual-head approach with a separate \"budget critic\" that explicitly predicts remaining budget could help the router learn to conserve writes, and having an independent answer head that gets protected gradient updates during the query phase would ensure it trains even when routing decisions go wrong. But looking at the actual numbers—blkd=0.71 means the answer head is essentially frozen during imitation learning because routing decisions are blocking most of the steps where it could learn.\n\nThe immediate fixes would be reducing the budget_B parameter so it lasts longer, switching to oracle routing for budget decisions instead of learned routing, or pre-allocating budget to guarantee the answer head gets enough steps to learn.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the core problem: the router is firing WRITE actions on steps where the oracle would fire PERCEIVE instead—those early encode steps shouldn't be writing at all. The routing head never learned that PERCEIVE steps (which map to SKIP in the routing) are the right move during encoding, so it's wasting writes on steps where nothing should be written. This is a routing policy failure, not a budget sizing problem. The training loop logs show that skip_frac stays constant at 0.79 while read_frac and write_frac are both around 0.11, which suggests the model isn't properly distinguishing between when to skip versus when to route to other actions.\n\nWait, but looking at the actual numbers—if write_frac is 0.11 and the episode is 190 steps with roughly 50 write-valid steps, that should only consume about 20 writes total. With budget_B=55, we should have plenty of headroom. So why is the blocking rate so high? Let me trace through the training loop to see where the disconnect is. during encode (i=0 to 99), genuine keys get WRITE and fillers get SKIP, so roughly half the encode steps should be writes. But during imitation learning, the model is feeding oracle actions, so it should be writing exactly when the oracle says to write. Let me trace through what's actually happening in the imitation phase—the model calls train_episode with oracle_routing=True, which means it's using the oracle schedule directly rather than making routing decisions. The issue might be that even with oracle routing, something in how the actions are being executed or logged is causing the discrepancy.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the model learns to route WRITE correctly during oracle mode, but the budget enforces a window constraint where only the last 100 steps matter. If the model fires WRITE too often early in the episode, it exhausts the budget window before reaching the query phase, which explains why the blocking rate is so high at 0.71 even though write_frac is only 0.11. The write actions that do get permitted are spread across the episode, but they consume enough of the 100-step window that later write attempts get blocked.\n\nThe real problem is that the router learns to be too \"aggressive\" with writes during imitation learning, then when it switches to free running, it keeps firing writes at the same rate but the budget is already depleted. A separate budget predictor could help the router learn to conserve writes, or we could add a constraint that guarantees some budget for query steps. But thinking about how infant architecture handles this—it has separate state encoders for working memory and recurring memory with a controller that selects which to use. The dual-head approach might actually help here by decoupling what gets stored from what gets routed.\n\nActually, looking at the memory write/read logic, the budget is enforced after routing decisions are made, so even if the dual-head approach would help with gradient flow, it wouldn't actually solve the core issue of writes happening before budget constraints kick in.\n\nThe real problem is that Phase 2 isn't training the answer head properly because the routing policy is too aggressive and depletes the budget. A few approaches could help: using a dual-head to separate gradient updates between the router and answer head so they don't interfere with each other, adding a learned budget predictor so the router knows when to conserve writes, or decoupling the budget signal from routing decisions entirely so the budget state doesn't get tangled up in what the router is trying to do. -fix would be to add a separate \"budget critic\" head that predicts remaining budget and is used ONLY for routing decisions, without affecting the answer head. This is more infant-like.\n\nOr, think about it differently: what if the dual head means one head for routing decisions and one head for answer predictions, and they have SEPARATE optimizers? This would prevent routing gradient from overwhelming answer gradient.\n\nLet me just give a concrete answer about whether dual-heads would help and how.","thinkingSignature":"43016f9461e9f2071c7d1c04b39e56b45a6526a7bd93c39ea19ceae134e295aa"},{"type":"text","text":"Yes — but for a specific reason, not the obvious one.\n\nThe \"infant\" dual-head has separate state encoders so the routing head and prediction head don't share gradient competition. But in SRMoE, they already don't share gradient directly — the answer head only gets signal during query steps, and routing happens everywhere.\n\nThe **actual problem** Phase 2 has: the learned router fires WRITE too aggressively, depleting the budget window before query phase. The blocking (blkd=0.71) means 71% of steps — including most query steps — are forced to SKIP, so the answer head barely gets trained.\n\nA dual-head setup *would* help if it's structured like this:\n\n**Head A (routing policy):** learns to route actions given hidden state + budget_remaining\n**Head B (budget critic):** learns to predict remaining budget given hidden state, SEPARATELY from the routing loss\n\nThe budget critic output gets fed INTO the routing head as an additional input — so the router learns \"I just wrote a lot, budget window is filling, I should SKIP for a while.\" The key insight: the budget signal goes INTO the routing decision, not AFTER it.\n\nThis is more infant-like in spirit — the budget critic is like infant's secondary encoding path, providing a separate signal that modulates the primary policy without gradient interference.\n\nQuick fix without restructuring: feed `budget_remaining` more aggressively into the router's encoder. Right now it's just one of 4 extra features — it might need a stronger pathway.\n\nWant me to look at the router encoder more closely and suggest how to strengthen the budget signal?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":2272,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":83219,"totalTokens":89780,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774355387936}}
{"type":"message","id":"e36ba0c6","parentId":"454034a5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:35:34.918Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"393\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 08:35 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nyes please. and explore the idea of a\"fractured\" or sharded head just for shits and gigs"}],"timestamp":1774355734912}}
{"type":"message","id":"c7772a6e","parentId":"e36ba0c6","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:35:55.999Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants me to:\n1. Look at the router encoder and suggest how to strengthen the budget signal\n2. Explore the idea of a \"fractured\" or sharded head\n\nLet me look at the relevant code more carefully. From the notebook:\n\n```python\nclass SRMoEHead(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, hidden_dim, n_codes=16, ring_dim=16, n_prefs=32,\n                 tau_start=1.0, tau_end=0.01, anneal_steps=5000, lambda_div=0.1):\n        ...\n        self.ring = RingAttractor(hidden_dim, ring_dim, n_prefs)\n\n\n```\n\nNow I'm examining the encoder architecture. It takes the hidden state, appends four additional features (budget remaining, step position, step parity, and query phase flag) along with the ring state projection, then passes this combined input through two linear layers with tanh activation to produce logits for each code in the codebook.\n\nThe `budget_remaining` feature gets concatenated as a raw scalar, but I'm wondering whether this is the right representation—maybe normalizing it or processing it through a deeper network path would help the router make better routing decisions. I should also consider how the ring attractor state is being projected and whether that's adequately capturing the temporal dynamics.\n\n```\nI'm also considering what a \"fractured\" or \"sharded\" head would look like here. The idea would be to split the routing head into multiple independent sub-heads that each specialize in different aspects—maybe one focused on budget constraints, another on query phase detection, and a third on position or parity signals. These would each have their own embedding of the hidden state, then get combined before the routing decision.\n```\nThis is similar to mixture of experts but applied within a single head itself. The sharded heads could also be cross-connected so that each shard sees different subsets of the input features. And the final routing decision would aggregate across all the shards.\n```\nI'm thinking about the \"fractured\" head concept as a way to avoid gradient starvation—similar to how the infant paper's dual heads prevent interference by separating representation learning from policy learning. A sharded head could mitigate the router's tendency to collapse by having each shard encode different aspects of the state, with a gating mechanism that combines them and a consensus mechanism for final routing decisions.","thinkingSignature":"04d95702556f5c61923898f8297c0e2adf5786ac67966dfc6f167672ee608907"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_jdxbx7q3p6hz_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb","offset":1,"limit":200}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":541,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":83699,"totalTokens":88529,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774355734916}}
{"type":"message","id":"3cb63885","parentId":"c7772a6e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:35:56.216Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_jdxbx7q3p6hz_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n \"cells\": [\n  {\n   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n   \"id\": \"b7bb99b5\",\n   \"metadata\": {},\n   \"source\": [\n    \"# SR-MoE Training\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"**Sparse Routing Mixture-of-Experts** with popcode VQ codebook + ring attractor.\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"This notebook trains the SR-MoE routing architecture end-to-end on the associative\\n\",\n    \"memory task. Run all cells in sequence.\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"## What is SR-MoE?\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"1. **Popcode Router** â€” replaces softmax with a learned VQ codebook. The router\\n\",\n    \"   selects a discrete codeword (one of N codes), each of which is a distribution\\n\",\n    \"   over the 3 routing actions. Closer to cortical sparse coding than MoE gating.\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"2. **Ring Attractor** â€” a 2D continuous attractor maintains routing state across\\n\",\n    \"   steps. Routing decisions depend on both the current token and the ring phase,\\n\",\n    \"   making routing path-dependent (vs stateless per-token softmax).\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"3. **Adversarial Diversity Regularizer** â€” penalizes code collapse (usage imbalance\\n\",\n    \"   + low code separation) so all codes stay active.\\n\"\n   ]\n  },\n  {\n   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n   \"execution_count\": null,\n   \"id\": \"0397ebd3\",\n   \"metadata\": {},\n   \"outputs\": [],\n   \"source\": [\n    \"import subprocess, sys\\n\",\n    \"subprocess.run([sys.executable, '-m', 'pip', 'install', 'numpy', 'wandb', '--quiet'], check=True)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"import os, math, random, json, time\\n\",\n    \"import torch\\n\",\n    \"import torch.nn as nn\\n\",\n    \"import torch.nn.functional as F\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"print('torch:', torch.__version__)\\n\",\n    \"print('GPU available:', torch.cuda.is_available())\\n\",\n    \"if torch.cuda.is_available():\\n\",\n    \"    print('GPU:', torch.cuda.get_device_name(0))\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"DEVICE = torch.device('cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')\\n\"\n   ]\n  },\n  {\n   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n   \"execution_count\": null,\n   \"id\": \"e0481840\",\n   \"metadata\": {},\n   \"outputs\": [],\n   \"source\": [\n    \"# Constants\\n\",\n    \"N_ACTIONS = 3   # SKIP=0, READ=1, WRITE=2\\n\",\n    \"ORACLE_TO_ACTION_IDX = {'SKIP': 0, 'READ': 1, 'WRITE': 2, 'PERCEIVE': 0}\\n\",\n    \"IGNORE_INDEX = -100\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"# Ring Attractor\\n\",\n    \"class RingAttractor(nn.Module):\\n\",\n    \"    def __init__(self, hidden_dim, ring_dim=16, n_prefs=32, dt=0.5, decay=0.95):\\n\",\n    \"        super().__init__()\\n\",\n    \"        self.hidden_dim = hidden_dim; self.ring_dim = ring_dim\\n\",\n    \"        self.n_prefs = n_prefs; self.dt = dt; self.decay = decay\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        self.register_buffer('_prefs',\\n\",\n    \"            torch.linspace(0, 2*math.pi, n_prefs, dtype=torch.float32))\\n\",\n    \"        self.input_proj = nn.Sequential(\\n\",\n    \"            nn.Linear(hidden_dim, ring_dim*2), nn.Tanh())\\n\",\n    \"        self.lateral_w = nn.Parameter(torch.zeros(n_prefs, n_prefs))\\n\",\n    \"        self._init_lateral_weights()\\n\",\n    \"        self._ring_state = None\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def _init_lateral_weights(self):\\n\",\n    \"        with torch.no_grad():\\n\",\n    \"            d = self._prefs.unsqueeze(1) - self._prefs.unsqueeze(0)\\n\",\n    \"            d = torch.atan2(torch.sin(d), torch.cos(d))\\n\",\n    \"            exc = torch.exp(-0.5*(d/2.0)**2)\\n\",\n    \"            inh = 0.3*torch.exp(-0.5*(d/5.0)**2)\\n\",\n    \"            w = (exc - inh) / (exc - inh).abs().mean() * 0.1\\n\",\n    \"            self.lateral_w.copy_(w)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def reset(self): self._ring_state = None\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def forward(self, hidden):\\n\",\n    \"        is_1d = hidden.dim() == 1\\n\",\n    \"        if is_1d: hidden = hidden.unsqueeze(0)\\n\",\n    \"        batch_size = hidden.shape[0]\\n\",\n    \"        ri = self.input_proj(hidden)\\n\",\n    \"        theta = torch.atan2(ri[..., 1], ri[..., 0])\\n\",\n    \"        prev = self._ring_state\\n\",\n    \"        if prev is None:\\n\",\n    \"            prev = torch.zeros(self.n_prefs, device=hidden.device)\\n\",\n    \"        prev_2d = prev.unsqueeze(0)\\n\",\n    \"        drive = F.relu(torch.cos(self._prefs.unsqueeze(0) - theta.unsqueeze(1)))\\n\",\n    \"        lateral = (self.lateral_w @ prev).unsqueeze(0).expand(batch_size, -1)\\n\",\n    \"        new_state = prev_2d + self.dt * (drive + 0.3*lateral - prev_2d - self.decay*prev_2d)\\n\",\n    \"        new_state = F.relu(new_state)\\n\",\n    \"        new_state = new_state / (new_state.sum(dim=-1, keepdim=True) + 1e-8)\\n\",\n    \"        self._ring_state = new_state.squeeze(0).detach()\\n\",\n    \"        return self._ring_state\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def get_state(self):\\n\",\n    \"        return self._ring_state if self._ring_state is not None else \\\\\\n\",\n    \"               torch.zeros(self.n_prefs, device=next(self.parameters()).device)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"# Diversity Regularizer\\n\",\n    \"class DiversityRegularizer(nn.Module):\\n\",\n    \"    def __init__(self, n_codes, lambda_usage=0.05, lambda_discrim=0.025):\\n\",\n    \"        super().__init__()\\n\",\n    \"        self.n_codes = n_codes\\n\",\n    \"        self.lambda_usage = lambda_usage\\n\",\n    \"        self.lambda_discrim = lambda_discrim\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def forward(self, codebook, pre_code_logits, code_indices):\\n\",\n    \"        device = codebook.device\\n\",\n    \"        batch_size = code_indices.shape[0]\\n\",\n    \"        usage_hist = torch.zeros(self.n_codes, device=device)\\n\",\n    \"        for idx in code_indices: usage_hist[idx] += 1\\n\",\n    \"        usage_p = usage_hist / (batch_size + 1e-8)\\n\",\n    \"        usage_entropy = -(usage_p * (usage_p + 1e-8).log()).sum()\\n\",\n    \"        usage_loss = 1.0 - usage_entropy / (math.log(self.n_codes) + 1e-8)\\n\",\n    \"        cb_probs = F.softmax(codebook, dim=-1)\\n\",\n    \"        discrimin_loss = torch.tensor(0.0, device=device)\\n\",\n    \"        n_pairs = 0\\n\",\n    \"        for i in range(self.n_codes):\\n\",\n    \"            for j in range(i+1, self.n_codes):\\n\",\n    \"                kl = F.kl_div(cb_probs[i].log().unsqueeze(0),\\n\",\n    \"                              cb_probs[j].unsqueeze(0), reduction='batchmean')\\n\",\n    \"                discrimin_loss += F.relu(0.5 - kl)\\n\",\n    \"                n_pairs += 1\\n\",\n    \"        if n_pairs > 0: discrimin_loss /= n_pairs\\n\",\n    \"        loss = self.lambda_usage * usage_loss + self.lambda_discrim * discrimin_loss\\n\",\n    \"        return loss, {'usage': usage_loss.item(), 'discrim': discrimin_loss.item()}\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"# SR-MoE Head\\n\",\n    \"class SRMoEHead(nn.Module):\\n\",\n    \"    def __init__(self, hidden_dim, n_codes=16, ring_dim=16, n_prefs=32,\\n\",\n    \"                 tau_start=1.0, tau_end=0.01, anneal_steps=5000, lambda_div=0.1):\\n\",\n    \"        super().__init__()\\n\",\n    \"        self.hidden_dim = hidden_dim; self.n_codes = n_codes\\n\",\n    \"        self._tau_start = tau_start; self._tau_end = tau_end\\n\",\n    \"        self.anneal_steps = anneal_steps\\n\",\n    \"        self._step = 0; self._eval_mode = False\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        self.ring = RingAttractor(hidden_dim, ring_dim, n_prefs)\\n\",\n    \"        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(\\n\",\n    \"            nn.Linear(hidden_dim + 4 + ring_dim, hidden_dim), nn.Tanh(),\\n\",\n    \"            nn.Linear(hidden_dim, n_codes))\\n\",\n    \"        self.ring_state_proj = nn.Linear(n_prefs, ring_dim)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        cb = torch.zeros(n_codes, N_ACTIONS)\\n\",\n    \"        for i in range(n_codes): cb[i, i % N_ACTIONS] = 1.0\\n\",\n    \"        self.codebook = nn.Parameter(cb)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        self.div_reg = DiversityRegularizer(n_codes,\\n\",\n    \"            lambda_usage=lambda_div*0.5, lambda_discrim=lambda_div*0.25)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    @property\\n\",\n    \"    def tau(self):\\n\",\n    \"        if self._eval_mode: return 0.0\\n\",\n    \"        frac = min(self._step / max(self.anneal_steps, 1), 1.0)\\n\",\n    \"        return self._tau_start + frac * (self._tau_end - self._tau_start)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def set_eval_mode(self, hard=True): self._eval_mode = hard\\n\",\n    \"    def reset(self): self._step = 0; self.ring.reset()\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def forward(self, hidden, budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase):\\n\",\n    \"        self._step += 1\\n\",\n    \"        h = hidden.view(-1)\\n\",\n    \"        self.ring(h)\\n\",\n    \"        rs = self.ring.get_state()\\n\",\n    \"        rp = torch.tanh(self.ring_state_proj(rs))\\n\",\n    \"        extra = torch.tensor([budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase],\\n\",\n    \"                           dtype=torch.float, device=hidden.device)\\n\",\n    \"        x = torch.cat([h, extra, rp], dim=-1)\\n\",\n    \"        pre_code = self.encoder(x)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        if self._eval_mode or self.tau <= 0:\\n\",\n    \"            code_idx = pre_code.argmax().item()\\n\",\n    \"        else:\\n\",\n    \"            gumbel = F.gumbel_softmax(pre_code.unsqueeze(0), tau=self.tau, hard=True)\\n\",\n    \"            code_idx = int(gumbel.argmax().item())\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        sel = F.embedding(torch.tensor([code_idx], device=hidden.device), self.codebook).squeeze(0)\\n\",\n    \"        action_logits = sel + (self.codebook[code_idx] - self.codebook[code_idx]).detach()\\n\",\n    \"        action_idx = int(action_logits.argmax().item())\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        probs = F.softmax(action_logits, dim=-1)\\n\",\n    \"        entropy = -(probs * (probs + 1e-9).log()).sum().item()\\n\",\n    \"        salience_entropy = entropy / math.log(N_ACTIONS)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        return action_logits, action_idx, salience_entropy\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def diversity_loss(self, hidden, budget_remaining):\\n\",\n\n[563 more lines in file. Use offset=201 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774355756106}}
{"type":"message","id":"c5a31e5c","parentId":"3cb63885","timestamp":"2026-03-24T12:37:06.529Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the code. Let me analyze the current structure and think about:\n\n1. **Budget signal strengthening**\n2. **Fractured/sharded head architecture**\n\n### Current Architecture Analysis\n\nThe encoder is:\n```python\nself.encoder = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(hidden_dim + 4 + ring_dim, hidden_dim), nn.Tanh(),\n    nn.Linear(hidden_dim, n_codes))\n```\n\nWhere `extra = [budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase]`.\n\nProblems I see:\n\n1. **`budget_remaining` is a raw scalar in [0, 1]`** — it's just concatenated into a high-dimensional space and has to fight for signal. A tiny linear projection from 1D to even 4D would be too weak to capture the importance of this signal.\n   \n2. **`step_pos` and `step_parity` are both raw values** — step_pos ranges [0,1] and step_parity is binary, but they're also just 4D inputs competing for attention in the concatenated feature space.\n\n3. **The ring projection `rp` dominates** — it's `ring_dim=16` dimensions, while the budget and step signals are only 4D total, so they get drowned out by the richer ring representation.\n\n4. **The extra features aren't normalized** — budget_remaining is already [0,1] but the other signals have different scales, making it hard for the network to learn meaningful interactions.\n\n### Budget Signal Strengthening\n\nThe core problem is that `budget_remaining` is only a single scalar feature among 4+16+128=141 total features. A better approach would be to expand budget_remaining into its own MLP that learns non-linear transformations of the budget state, capturing budget pressure, budget velocity (rate of change), and other derived signals.\n\nThis expanded representation should then be concatenated with hidden and ring_proj before the encoder, giving the network richer budget-aware features to work with. I'm also considering adding a budget critic network that explicitly learns to predict the value of budget states, similar to a value function in reinforcement learning, which would provide an auxiliary training signal and help the router understand when budget is plentiful versus scarce.\n\nA fractured or sharded routing head would split the encoding path into separate shards that each specialize in different aspects of the routing decision.\n\nI'm exploring two sharding strategies: feature-partitioned shards where each shard processes different subsets of input features, and cross-connected shards where each shard sees the full input but uses separate parameters. The key mechanism would be a gating function that aggregates shard outputs through learned weights, combined with an attention-based fusion layer.\n\nThere's an interesting connection here to mixture of experts—the difference is that MoE routes to whole experts while this approach routes within a single expert's computation. I'm also considering a simpler alternative where the codebook itself is fractured into k clusters, with routing decisions happening first at the cluster level before selecting within clusters, creating a hierarchical routing structure.\n\nThis hierarchical approach could naturally distribute specialization across clusters, making the system more robust to code collapse—if one cluster dies, others still function. I'm also thinking about how this connects to infant's dual-head architecture and how each head might use different feature representations for the same underlying state.\n\nI should write out concrete code modifications to show how these ideas would work in practice, then address the actual question about whether the dual-head mechanism would help SRMoE, which really comes down to whether routing and prediction heads would benefit from separate representations or shared computation.\n\nThe routing head needs to compress state down to action distributions while tracking budget constraints, whereas the prediction head just needs to map hidden states to value predictions. These are fundamentally different computations, so separating them would reduce interference and let each head develop specialized internal representations rather than forcing them to compete within a single network.\n\nNow I'm seeing that the dual-head setup actually creates two pathways: one that learns a budget-aware representation and another that predicts value given that representation, with the routing policy taking the budget critic's output as an additional input. This means the routing head receives richer, more structured information about budget constraints rather than having to infer everything from raw state. Let me draft this out properly.","thinkingSignature":"f4ef0961e2b2f99d463bb549539943d452f922fa91bc5818bd237b36bc0fb2fd"},{"type":"text","text":"OK, I see the full picture now. Here's my analysis of both ideas:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Strengthening the Budget Signal (Quick Fix)\n\n**Current problem:** `budget_remaining` is a single raw scalar `[0,1]` concatenated into 141-dimensional input (`hidden=128 + extra=4 + ring_proj=16`). It gets one column in a linear layer projecting to 128-dim. That's way too weak — the network can't learn the budget dynamics properly from that thin a signal.\n\n**Fix:** Expand `budget_remaining` into a rich multi-feature vector *before* feeding to the encoder:\n\n```python\n# In SRMoEHead.__init__, replace the thin extra concatenation with:\nself.budget_encoder = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(4, 32), nn.Tanh(),   # 4 budget features → 32-dim\n    nn.Linear(32, 16), nn.Tanh()   # → 16-dim rich budget embedding\n)\nself.ring_state_proj = nn.Linear(n_prefs, ring_dim)\nself.step_encoder = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(3, 8), nn.Tanh()     # step_pos, step_parity, is_query → 8-dim\n)\n# Encoder now gets: h(128) + budget_emb(16) + ring_proj(16) + step_emb(8) = 168 dim\nself.encoder = nn.Sequential(\n    nn.Linear(hidden_dim + 16 + ring_dim + 8, hidden_dim), nn.Tanh(),\n    nn.Linear(hidden_dim, n_codes))\n```\n\nAnd in `forward`, replace the raw extra with learned embeddings:\n\n```python\nextra_rich = torch.tensor([budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase],\n                           dtype=torch.float, device=hidden.device)\nbudget_emb = self.budget_encoder(extra_rich.unsqueeze(0)).squeeze(0)\nstep_emb = self.step_encoder(torch.tensor([step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase],\n                                           dtype=torch.float, device=hidden.device))\nx = torch.cat([h, budget_emb, rp, step_emb], dim=-1)\n```\n\nThis gives the budget signal 32 params of dedicated nonlinear processing instead of 1 column in a linear layer.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Fractured/Sharded Head (More Interesting)\n\nThe \"fractured\" idea: split the single encoder into **k Shards**, each a small independent encoder that sees a *different subset* of the input, then **fuse** their outputs. The Shards are forced to specialize because they don't share parameters or gradient flow.\n\n```python\nclass ShardedSRMoEHead(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"\n    Fractured routing head: k shards, each a small encoder over different features.\n    A lightweight fusion module aggregates shard outputs into routing logits.\n\n    Intuition: instead of one monolithic encoder that compresses everything into\n    one representation, we force multiple independent \"views\" of the state,\n    reducing gradient starvation and collapse.\n    \"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, hidden_dim, n_codes=16, ring_dim=16, n_prefs=32,\n                 n_shards=4, tau_start=1.0, tau_end=0.01, anneal_steps=5000,\n                 lambda_div=0.1):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.hidden_dim = hidden_dim; self.n_codes = n_codes\n        self.n_shards = n_shards\n        self._tau_start = tau_start; self._tau_end = tau_end\n        self.anneal_steps = anneal_steps\n        self._step = 0; self._eval_mode = False\n\n        self.ring = RingAttractor(hidden_dim, ring_dim, n_prefs)\n        self.ring_state_proj = nn.Linear(n_prefs, ring_dim)\n\n        # Shard 1: hidden state only (the core representation)\n        self.shard_hidden = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(hidden_dim, 64), nn.Tanh(),\n            nn.Linear(64, 32))\n\n        # Shard 2: budget + step features (temporal context)\n        self.shard_budget = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(4, 32), nn.Tanh(),    # budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query\n            nn.Linear(32, 16))\n\n        # Shard 3: ring state (attractor dynamics)\n        self.shard_ring = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(ring_dim, 32), nn.Tanh(),\n            nn.Linear(32, 16))\n\n        # Shard 4: cross-features (hidden × budget interaction)\n        self.shard_cross = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(hidden_dim + 4, 48), nn.Tanh(),\n            nn.Linear(48, 24))\n\n        # Fusion: aggregate shard outputs into pre-code logits\n        total_shard_dim = 32 + 16 + 16 + 24  # = 88\n        self.fusion = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(total_shard_dim, hidden_dim), nn.Tanh(),\n            nn.Linear(hidden_dim, n_codes))\n\n        # Optional: a \"consensus\" module — each shard votes on the action\n        # then the vote is fused with the main routing decision\n        self.shard_vote_weights = nn.Sequential(\n            nn.Linear(total_shard_dim, n_shards))  # per-shard confidence\n\n        # Codebook\n        cb = torch.zeros(n_codes, N_ACTIONS)\n        for i in range(n_codes): cb[i, i % N_ACTIONS] = 1.0\n        self.codebook = nn.Parameter(cb)\n\n        self.div_reg = DiversityRegularizer(n_codes,\n            lambda_usage=lambda_div*0.5, lambda_discrim=lambda_div*0.25)\n\n    @property\n    def tau(self):\n        if self._eval_mode: return 0.0\n        frac = min(self._step / max(self.anneal_steps, 1), 1.0)\n        return self._tau_start + frac * (self._tau_end - self._tau_start)\n\n    def set_eval_mode(self, hard=True): self._eval_mode = hard\n    def reset(self): self._step = 0; self.ring.reset()\n\n    def forward(self, hidden, budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase):\n        self._step += 1\n        h = hidden.view(-1)\n\n        # Ring attractor\n        self.ring(h)\n        rs = self.ring.get_state()\n        rp = torch.tanh(self.ring_state_proj(rs))\n\n        # Fractured encoding — each shard processes independently\n        shard_h = self.shard_hidden(h)\n        extra = torch.tensor([budget_remaining, step_pos, step_parity, is_query_phase],\n                             dtype=torch.float, device=hidden.device)\n        shard_b = self.shard_budget(extra)\n        shard_r = self.shard_ring(rp)\n        shard_c = self.shard_cross(torch.cat([h, extra], dim=-1))\n\n        # Concatenate shard embeddings\n        shard_emb = torch.cat([shard_h, shard_b, shard_r, shard_c], dim=-1)\n\n        # Per-shard vote weights (how much to trust each shard for this decision)\n        vote_w = F.softmax(self.shard_vote_weights(shard_emb), dim=-1)  # [n_shards]\n\n        # Fuse to routing logits\n        pre_code = self.fusion(shard_emb)\n\n        # Optional: bias fusion toward shards that are \"confident\"\n        # (confidence = entropy of vote_w, low entropy = trust that shard)\n        vote_confidence = 1.0 - (vote_w * (vote_w + 1e-9).log()).sum() / math.log(self.n_shards)\n        pre_code = pre_code + vote_confidence.detach() * (vote_w @ torch.stack([\n            shard_h, shard_b, shard_r, shard_c]).chunk(self.n_shards, 0)).squeeze(0)\n\n        if self._eval_mode or self.tau <= 0:\n            code_idx = pre_code.argmax().item()\n        else:\n            gumbel = F.gumbel_softmax(pre_code.unsqueeze(0), tau=self.tau, hard=True)\n            code_idx = int(gumbel.argmax().item())\n\n        sel = F.embedding(torch.tensor([code_idx], device=hidden.device), self.codebook).squeeze(0)\n        action_logits = sel + (self.codebook[code_idx] - self.codebook[code_idx]).detach()\n        action_idx = int(action_logits.argmax().item())\n\n        probs = F.softmax(action_logits, dim=-1)\n        entropy = -(probs * (probs + 1e-9).log()).sum().item()\n        salience_entropy = entropy / math.log(N_ACTIONS)\n\n        return action_logits, action_idx, salience_entropy\n```\n\n**Why this helps prevent collapse:**\n- Each shard has its own parameters — if one shard corrupts, others still route\n- The cross-shard fusion means no single shard can dominate\n- `shard_budget` has dedicated capacity for budget dynamics, solving the thin-signal problem above\n- `shard_ring` isolates attractor dynamics, so ring state and budget state don't compete\n\n**Connection to infant's dual-head:** The fractured head is essentially `k` mini dual-heads, each with its own representation path. The fusion module plays the role of the \"policy\" head, consuming representations from multiple specialized \"state\" heads simultaneously.\n\n---\n\n**For Phase 2 collapse specifically**, the fractured budget shard would likely be the biggest win — it isolates the budget signal processing so the router can actually learn \"WRITE only when budget is healthy AND ring phase says to write.\" Right now that signal is getting crushed in a 141-dim soup.\n\nWant me to write the full modified `SRMoE_Training.ipynb` with both fixes applied, or just the budget encoder first to test quickly?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":77239,"output":2945,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":94359,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774355756219}}
