{"type":"message","id":"83a3850e","parentId":"eb4c0ddf","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:11:39.541Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking about quadrupling the batch size for training. Let me think about this in context of SRMoE training.\n\nCurrently the training setup seems to use a certain batch size (probably 1 episode per train_episode call based on what I saw in the notebook). \n\nWait, looking at the training loop - it calls `trainer.train_episode(generate_episode(DEEPSEED + ep), use_oracle_routing=True)` - so each `train_episode` runs one episode at a time. There might not be batch size in the traditional sense here.\n\nBut actually, looking at the trainer code more carefully - each episode is processed step by step within `train_episode`, and the gradients are accumulated within that episode. \n\nSo the real question is whether Zach should run multiple episodes per optimizer step instead of just one. With a larger batch of episodes processed together, I'd get better gradient estimates and more stable training, though the memory cost would scale linearly since each episode carries its own routing state through the GRU. For SRMoE specifically, the fractured head with four shards already adds some overhead, but that shouldn't be the bottleneck - the routing decisions and memory interactions are where the actual compute load sits.\n\nWith quadrupled batch size, the diversity regularizer would also see more code usage per step, which could help with representation learning. The Phase 1 results showed solid performance at epoch 600 with accuracy around 0.850, so the model seems to be learning reasonably well already.\n\nBut Phase 2 is where things get interesting - if the oracle routing in Phase 1 isn't being learned properly, then the bottleneck might not be about gradient statistics at all. The real problem is likely that the imitation learning phase isn't giving the answer head enough training signal because the learned router fires WRITE too aggressively and drains the budget. Tripling or quadrupling the batch size could help by providing more diverse routing experiences per step, though I should also consider whether the BudgetEnforcer's block rate is even the right bottleneck to address.\n\nIf blocking is the core issue, then better budget-aware routing would be more valuable than simply increasing batch size. But if the model is already learning reasonable routing and just needs more data, then yes - tripling batch size would give three times as many routing decisions per optimizer step, which could speed things up noticeably. The memory overhead from the additional GRUs and routing states across episodes would be manageable, though it would scale with the batch size.\n\nI should check what batch size is actually being used in the training setup, since that would tell me whether scaling to 4 episodes per step is feasible or if I'm already near the memory limit.","thinkingSignature":"41395ce4b5a084ce03dd46d89334113b95de18c1a9b3d2a0e1e800e851578296"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ylcpjqke8q0j_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb","offset":650,"limit":120}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":597,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":95082,"totalTokens":99968,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774357874362}}
{"type":"message","id":"24b7e9aa","parentId":"83a3850e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:11:39.639Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ylcpjqke8q0j_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"    \"            logits, info = m(tok)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"            r_logits_list.append(info['routing_logits'])\\n\",\n    \"            oa = episode.oracle_actions[t]\\n\",\n    \"            oracle_labels.append(ORACLE_TO_ACTION_IDX.get(oa, IGNORE_INDEX))\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"            ai = info['action_idx']\\n\",\n    \"            action_idx_list.append(ai)       # route density tracking\\n\",\n    \"            self._action_idx_list.append(ai)  # FIX #4: for density loss\\n\",\n    \"            if ai == 0: skip_cnt += 1\\n\",\n    \"            elif ai == 1: read_cnt += 1\\n\",\n    \"            elif ai == 2: write_cnt += 1\\n\",\n    \"            if info.get('blocked'): blocked_cnt += 1\\n\",\n    \"            if t < QUERY_START:\\n\",\n    \"                encode_occupancies.append(info['occupancy'])\\n\",\n    \"                encode_saliences.append(info['salience_entropy'])\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"            if tgt != IGNORE_INDEX:\\n\",\n    \"                answer_logits.append(logits); answer_targets.append(tgt)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        n_steps = len(episode.input_ids)\\n\",\n    \"        skip_frac = skip_cnt / n_steps\\n\",\n    \"        read_frac = read_cnt / n_steps\\n\",\n    \"        write_frac = write_cnt / n_steps\\n\",\n    \"        blocked_frac = blocked_cnt / max(n_steps, 1)\\n\",\n    \"        avg_occupancy = sum(encode_occupancies) / max(len(encode_occupancies), 1)\\n\",\n    \"        avg_salience = sum(encode_saliences) / max(len(encode_saliences), 1)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        r_t = torch.stack(r_logits_list)\\n\",\n    \"        # FIX #5: mask out encode-phase SKIP labels from route CE\\n\",\n    \"        # Oracle SKIP during encode is a crutch, not a real routing decision\\n\",\n    \"        r_lbl = torch.tensor(oracle_labels, dtype=torch.long, device=DEVICE)\\n\",\n    \"        route_mask = torch.ones_like(r_lbl, dtype=torch.bool)  # default: include\\n\",\n    \"        for ti, oa in enumerate(oracle_labels):\\n\",\n    \"            if oa == IGNORE_INDEX:\\n\",\n    \"                route_mask[ti] = False\\n\",\n    \"            elif oa == 0 and ti < QUERY_START:  # SKIP during encode — skip this label\\n\",\n    \"                route_mask[ti] = False\\n\",\n    \"        if route_mask.sum() > 0:\\n\",\n    \"            masked_r_t = r_t[route_mask]\\n\",\n    \"            masked_r_lbl = r_lbl[route_mask]\\n\",\n    \"            r_wt = torch.tensor(self.route_class_weights, dtype=torch.float, device=DEVICE)\\n\",\n    \"        L_route = F.cross_entropy(r_t, r_lbl, weight=r_wt, ignore_index=IGNORE_INDEX)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        L_answer = torch.tensor(0.0, device=DEVICE); accuracy = 0.0\\n\",\n    \"        if answer_logits:\\n\",\n    \"            a_t = torch.stack(answer_logits)\\n\",\n    \"            a_l = torch.tensor(answer_targets, dtype=torch.long, device=DEVICE)\\n\",\n    \"            L_answer = F.cross_entropy(a_t, a_l)\\n\",\n    \"            accuracy = (a_t.argmax(-1)==a_l).float().mean().item()\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        L_margin = torch.tensor(0.0, device=DEVICE)\\n\",\n    \"        if self.lambda_margin > 0 and len(r_logits_list) > 0:\\n\",\n    \"            all_r = torch.stack(r_logits_list)\\n\",\n    \"            L_margin = self._margin_loss(all_r[:,2], all_r[:,0])\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        L_div = torch.tensor(0.0, device=DEVICE); div_comp = {}\\n\",\n    \"        if self.lambda_div > 0 and hasattr(m.routing, 'diversity_loss'):\\n\",\n    \"            L_div, div_comp = m.routing.diversity_loss(\\n\",\n    \"                m._hidden.detach(), m.budget.budget_remaining_normalised)\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        L_density = self._density_loss(self._action_idx_list)  # FIX #4\\n\",\n    \"        loss = L_answer + self.lambda_route*L_route + self.lambda_margin*L_margin + self.lambda_div*L_div + (L_density if L_density is not None else torch.tensor(0.0, device=DEVICE))\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        self.opt.zero_grad(); loss.backward()\\n\",\n    \"        torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(self.params, 1.0); self.opt.step()\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        # wandb logging\\n\",\n    \"        if self._wandb_run is not None:\\n\",\n    \"            self._wandb_run.log({\\n\",\n    \"                'train/loss': loss.item(),\\n\",\n    \"                'train/answer_loss': L_answer.item(),\\n\",\n    \"                'train/route_loss': L_route.item(),\\n\",\n    \"                'train/margin_loss': L_margin.item(),\\n\",\n    \"                'train/div_loss': L_div.item(),\\n\",\n    \"                'train/accuracy': accuracy,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/skip_frac': skip_frac,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/read_frac': read_frac,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/write_frac': write_frac,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/blocked_frac': blocked_frac,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/avg_encode_occupancy': avg_occupancy,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/avg_salience_entropy': avg_salience,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/tau': m.routing.tau if hasattr(m.routing, 'tau') else 0.0,\\n\",\n    \"                'train/div_usage': div_comp.get('usage', 0.0),\\n\",\n    \"                'train/div_discrim': div_comp.get('discrim', 0.0),\\n\",\n    \"            }, step=self._ep_count)\\n\",\n    \"            self._ep_count += 1\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"        return {\\n\",\n    \"            'loss': loss.item(), 'answer_loss': L_answer.item(),\\n\",\n    \"            'route_loss': L_route.item(), 'margin_loss': L_margin.item(),\\n\",\n    \"            'div_loss': L_div.item(), 'accuracy': accuracy,\\n\",\n    \"            'skip_frac': skip_frac, 'read_frac': read_frac, 'write_frac': write_frac,\\n\",\n    \"            'blocked_frac': blocked_frac, 'avg_occupancy': avg_occupancy,\\n\",\n    \"            'avg_salience': avg_salience, 'div_components': div_comp,\\n\",\n    \"        }\\n\",\n    \"\\n\",\n    \"    def eval_free(self, episodes, hard=True):\\n\",\n    \"        m = self.model.eval()\\n\",\n    \"        correct, total = 0, 0\\n\",\n    \"        write_margins, skip_fracs, read_fracs, write_fracs = [], [], [], []\\n\",\n    \"        encode_occupancies = []\\n\",\n    \"        with torch.no_grad():\\n\",\n    \"            for ep in episodes:\\n\",\n    \"                m.reset_episode()\\n\",\n    \"                if hasattr(m.routing, 'set_eval_mode'): m.routing.set_eval_mode(hard)\\n\",\n    \"                for t in range(len(ep.input_ids)):\\n\",\n    \"                    tok = ep.input_ids[t].to(DEVICE)\\n\",\n    \"                    tgt = ep.target_value_ids[t].item()\\n\",\n    \"                    logits, info = m(tok, route_stop_grad=True)\\n\",\n    \"                    if t >= QUERY_START and tgt != IGNORE_INDEX:\\n\",\n    \"                        correct += int(logits.argmax().item() == tgt); total += 1\\n\",\n    \"                    ai = info['action_idx']\\n\",\n    \"                    r = info.get('routing_logits')\\n\",\n    \"                    if r is not None and r.shape[-1] >= 3:\\n\",\n    \"                        write_margins.append((r[2]-r[0]).item())\\n\",\n    \"                    skip_fracs.append(1.0 if ai==0 else 0.0)\\n\",\n    \"                    read_fracs.append(1.0 if ai==1 else 0.0)\\n\",\n    \"                    write_fracs.append(1.0 if ai==2 else 0.0)\\n\",\n    \"                    if t < QUERY_START:\\n\",\n\n[293 more lines in file. Use offset=770 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774357899590}}
{"type":"message","id":"0f6378c1","parentId":"24b7e9aa","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:12:22.788Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the training loop clearly. Each `train_episode` processes exactly ONE episode, then does one backward pass. There's no batch size > 1 in the traditional sense.\n\nZach is asking about processing multiple episodes per optimizer step. This would be:\n\nOption A: Gradient accumulation — process B episodes, accumulate gradients, then step\nOption B: True batch — process B episodes simultaneously with batched GPU operations\n\nFor this architecture, Option A (gradient accumulation) is the cleanest approach since each episode has its own routing state (GRU hidden, ring state, budget state). You'd do:\n\n```python\nfor ep in range(PRETRAIN_EPS):\n\n\n```\n\nThe tradeoff is clear: 4x more episodes per optimizer step means 4x fewer weight updates for the same wall clock time, but each update has 4x more signal. For Phase 1 with oracle routing, this would stabilize gradients and improve diversity estimation. For Phase 2 with learned routing, the fractured head has enough parameters that more data per step should help it learn better.\n\nThe real constraint is memory—each episode maintains separate GRU hidden states, ring states, budget buffers, and memory contents. With B episodes, I'd need to store all that state separately before aggregating gradients. With 4 shards × ~150 parameters each, that's manageable, but the memory overhead scales linearly with batch size.\n\nNow I'm weighing whether the fractured head is actually the limiting factor. The shard_vote_net has around 400 parameters, which is tiny compared to the fusion network at ~12K params. The fusion and confidence_proj together account for most of the parameters, so the routing head itself probably isn't the bottleneck—it's more likely the overall model capacity or the learning dynamics of the shard routing itself.\n\nBut here's the thing: quadrupling the batch size wouldn't actually help Phase 2 collapse if the problem is that the budget is draining too fast. The issue isn't about statistical estimates—the model would still see diverse experiences with batch=1. The real fix is making the routing head budget-aware so it doesn't fire WRITE so aggressively in the first place.\n\nThat said, if Phase 2 isn't collapsing and we're just training slowly, then batch scaling could speed things up noticeably. Going from 1 to 4 episodes per step means 4x fewer optimizer steps needed, which could cut training time substantially. The memory overhead would be manageable too—4x separate states shouldn't exceed GPU capacity.\n\nThe tradeoff is that we'll hit the accuracy ceiling faster with fewer steps, but if Phase 1 accuracy is already good around epoch 600, then batch=4 might get us there in 150 episodes instead of 600. I should focus my answer on whether batch scaling actually addresses the Phase 2 collapse problem or if it's just a speed optimization, and what the practical considerations are for implementation.\n\n```\n- batch=4 via gradient accumulation is the cleanest approach\n- Phase 1 benefits most from better gradient estimates\n- Phase 2 has mixed effects: slower collapse but slower learning\n- memory overhead is acceptable for 4 episodes\n```","thinkingSignature":"d58270f02779c798952dfcc25df6283674448d54337ece231a715988631ca79e"},{"type":"text","text":"Current setup: 1 episode → 1 backward pass → 1 optimizer step. Each `train_episode` call is fully isolated. No batch dimension.\n\nTripling/quadrupling would be gradient accumulation — process N episodes, accumulate gradients, then one `opt.step()`. Here's the honest breakdown:\n\n**Where it helps:**\n- **Phase 1 (oracle routing)** — 4× more routing decisions per weight update = smoother gradients, better diversity estimates from the regularizer, less gradient noise. This is where it wins.\n- **Diversity regularizer** — more episodes per step = more stable code usage histograms → the `usage_entropy` and `discrim_loss` become more reliable\n\n**Where it's neutral or backfires:**\n- **Phase 2 (learned routing)** — the *speed* of collapse might actually increase. More episodes per step means the router sees more WRITE-fires faster, drains budget faster, hits blocking sooner. But the total number of optimizer steps is the same (fewer steps, same total episodes processed), so the wall-clock time to collapse is reduced. If the model survives longer on batch=1 because each step is more conservative, batch=4 might collapse at ~the same episode count but in ¼ the time. That's a loss.\n- **Memory** — each episode carries its own GRU hidden, ring state, budget buffer, and memory content. With 4 episodes accumulated: 4× overhead. For RTX 5000 with 16GB this should be fine — the biggest consumer is the GRU (128-dim hidden) and the shards are small (~12K params total for the routing head).\n\n**Recommendation:** If you're going to try it, do it for Phase 1 only, then switch to batch=1 for Phase 2. Something like:\n\n```python\nBATCH_SIZE = 4  # gradient accumulation\nACCUM_STEPS = BATCH_SIZE\n\nfor ep in range(PRETRAIN_EP):\n    stats = trainer.train_episode(generate_episode(DEEPSEED + ep))\n    accum_loss += stats['loss'] / ACCUM_STEPS\n    if (ep + 1) % ACCUM_STEPS == 0:\n        accum_loss.backward()  # deferred\n        torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(trainer.params, 1.0)\n        trainer.opt.step()\n        trainer.opt.zero_grad()\n        accum_loss = 0.0\n```\n\nThat said — the fractured head is already the bigger lever for Phase 2. Get Phase 2 working first, then scale batch if you want faster Phase 1 convergence."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":87816,"output":1158,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":103149,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774357899641}}
{"type":"message","id":"e48d9175","parentId":"0f6378c1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:16:58.283Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"484\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 09:16 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nokay its still running. what are your thoughts on using dagger?/"}],"timestamp":1774358218279}}
{"type":"message","id":"52ac482e","parentId":"e48d9175","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:17:31.688Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking about DAgger (Dataset Aggregation) for the SRMoE training. Let me think through this carefully.\n\nDAgger is a imitation learning technique where you:\n1. Train a policy\n2. Run the policy to collect trajectories\n3. At each step, ask the oracle what the optimal action would have been\n4. Add those (state, oracle_action) pairs to the training data\n5. Repeat\n\nThe key difference from pure imitation learning (which just trains on oracle demonstrations) is that DAgger collects data from the actual state distributions the learned policy encounters - not just the oracle distribution. This addresses the distributional shift problem.\n \nThe current Phase 2 setup uses a schedule where the model starts following the oracle for a certain number of steps, then switches to its own routing decisions. DAgger would be more elegant than this forced switching mechanism - instead of manually deciding when to let the learned policy take over, the model gradually trains on increasingly realistic states where it has to make routing decisions, with the oracle providing the correct actions at each point.\n\nThe key insight is that Phase 1 trains exclusively on oracle-routed episodes, so the model never sees the actual states it would encounter when using learned routing. DAgger solves this by alternating between running the current policy to reach a state, then querying the oracle for what it would do there, and retraining on that aggregated dataset. This way the model learns from the true state distribution it actually faces, rather than from a simulated one. The main risk with DAgger is that if the model makes a catastrophic routing error early on, it could drive the episode into an unrecoverable state, but since the SRMoE setup with budget enforcement might be robust to that kind of failure, it could be worth exploring.","thinkingSignature":"dc1037f0fa1b138d6e6f48934f835853aeddfb440ba130508268f2cc293159c0"},{"type":"text","text":"DAgger = Dataset Aggregation. Instead of just training on oracle-routed episodes (what Phase 1 does) or letting the learned policy run unsupervised (what Phase 2's `use_oracle_routing=False` does), you run the current policy, and at every step you also ask the oracle \"what would you have done here?\" and add that (state, oracle_action) pair to the training set.\n\n**Why it matters here:**\n\nPhase 1 trains the model on oracle-routed episodes. But oracle routing and learned routing visit *different state distributions* — the router makes different memory states, different ring phases, different budget levels. So Phase 1 trains on a distribution the model never actually sees in Phase 2. Classic distributional shift.\n\nDAgger fixes that: you collect trajectories from the learned policy, query the oracle at each step, and train on those (state, oracle_action) pairs. The training distribution now matches the inference distribution.\n\n**How it would look for SRMoE:**\n\nInstead of the current schedule (`use_oracle_routing=True` for N episodes, then `False`), you'd do:\n\n```python\nfor ep in range(TOTAL):\n    # Run current policy (may be partially learned)\n    stats, trajectory = run_episode_with_trajectory(model, episode)\n    \n    # For each step, also get what the oracle would have done\n    for step, state in enumerate(trajectory):\n        oracle_action = get_oracle_action(state)\n        dagger_buffer.append(state, oracle_action)\n    \n    # Train on DAgger buffer (sampled) + fresh oracle episodes\n    batch = sample(dagger_buffer, batch_size) + [generate_episode()]\n    train(batch)\n```\n\n**The catch — the compounding error problem:**\n\nThe classic DAgger failure mode: early in training the policy is bad → visits bad states → oracle labels are for those bad states → trains on bad states → policy gets worse. The compounding error spiral.\n\nIn SRMoE specifically, the risk is: bad routing drains the budget → query phase has no memory content → oracle says READ but there's nothing useful to read → model trains on nonsensical (state, oracle_action) pairs. This could corrupt the answer head training.\n\nMitigation: a **DAgger safety margin** — if the learned policy's budget_remaining drops below a threshold, fall back to oracle routing for the remainder of that episode. This limits how bad states can get.\n\n**My read:** DAgger is the theoretically correct approach for Phase 2 and could fix the collapse problem more elegantly than the fractured head. The budget shard fix and the fractured head address *capacity* — making sure the router can learn budget dynamics. DAgger addresses the *distribution* — making sure the router trains on the right states.\n\nIf Phase 2 is still collapsing after the fractured head, DAgger is the next lever. But it's more invasive — you'd need to modify the training loop to collect trajectories and maintain a replay buffer. Worth doing if the fractured head alone isn't enough."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":987,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":97829,"totalTokens":103105,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774358218282}}
{"type":"message","id":"38f7f358","parentId":"52ac482e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:19:24.997Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"487\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 09:19 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nokay make a note of that and explain th esignificance of the project and novel discoveries made if any?"}],"timestamp":1774358364992}}
{"type":"message","id":"bb14c7e6","parentId":"38f7f358","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:20:01.868Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants me to:\n1. Make a note about DAgger in the workspace memory/notes\n2. Explain the significance of the SRMoE project and any novel discoveries\n\nLet me write this up properly in the memory files.","thinkingSignature":"046bf850b2e097d1c452b46d9522a86aaff19a228f39b2fca485025f42710341"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xhv7d4re585d_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-24.md","content":"# 2026-03-24\n\n## SRMoE / HGSEL Project\n\n**Location:** `C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb`\n**Project name:** SR-MoE = Sparse Routing Mixture of Experts (aka HGSEL = Hash-based Sparse Expert Layer, located at `C:\\dev\\research\\hgsel-moe`)\n\n### What it is\nAssociative memory task: model sees 50 key-value pairs over 190 steps, must store them in external memory, then answer queries (given key, retrieve value) during a query phase.\n\nThe architecture replaces softmax gating with a discrete VQ codebook + ring attractor for path-dependent routing. The router selects from N codes, each code is a distribution over {SKIP, READ, WRITE}. Three phases:\n- **Phase 1:** Oracle routing — model learns to use memory correctly while router watches\n- **Phase 2:** Learned routing (imitation learning) — oracle schedule fades, router takes over\n- **Phase 3:** Free run — no oracle, fully learned policy\n\n### Current problem (was Phase 2 collapse)\nThe learned router fires WRITE too aggressively during imitation learning, exhausting the budget window before query phase. The model never gets to practice the answer head. Symptoms: acc=0.000, blkd=0.71 (71% of steps blocked by budget).\n\n**Root cause:** `budget_remaining` was a single raw scalar concatenated into a 141-dim input (hidden=128 + 4 extra features + ring_proj=16). The budget signal was 1 column in a linear layer — way too thin for the network to learn budget dynamics.\n\n### Fix applied: FracturedSRMoEHead\nReplaced the monolithic encoder with 4 independent shards, each processing a different input subset:\n- `shard_hidden` (128 → 64 → 32): core hidden state\n- `shard_budget` (4 → 32 → 16): **budget + step features, dedicated pathway — THE key fix**\n- `shard_ring` (16 → 32 → 16): ring attractor projection\n- `shard_cross` (132 → 48 → 24): hidden × budget cross-features\n\nPlus a fusion network, per-shard confidence weighting, and a confidence_proj to map the 32-dim bias into n_codes space.\n\n**Notebook changes:** New cell (cell 2) defines `FracturedSRMoEHead` and aliases `SRMoEHead = FracturedSRMoEHead`. Old `class SRMoEHead` removed from constants cell (cell 3). ArchitectureB (cell 4) picks it up via alias.\n\n### DAgger consideration (not yet implemented)\nDAgger = Dataset Aggregation. Instead of Phase 1 → Phase 2 (oracle → learned), run the current policy and collect (state, oracle_action) pairs. Train on both the DAgger buffer and fresh oracle episodes. Addresses distributional shift between oracle-routed training states and learned-routed inference states.\n\nClassic failure mode: compounding error spiral. In SRMoE, risk is bad routing drains budget → query phase has no content → oracle labels become nonsensical → model trains on garbage.\n\nMitigation options if needed:\n1. Budget safety threshold — fall back to oracle if budget_remaining drops below threshold\n2. DAgger buffer with oracle-only labels (don't label bad states with oracle actions that assume good memory state)\n3. Conservative DAgger mixing — only inject DAgger data when the policy is already partially good\n\n## EXP / CAAE Project\n\n**Location:** `C:\\dev\\EXP`\n**Key results (from 2026-03-22 compound experiments):**\n\n- **Exp 7** (shared KV pooling): 65.8% memory reduction avg, up to 77.2% on realistic profile\n- **Exp 9** (multi-GPU NVLink): 3.08x throughput improvement, 42% P99 latency reduction, 5.3x NVLink utilization increase\n- **Exp 13** (production trace replay): 65.1% P99 latency improvement (vs 54.3% expected), SLA compliance 81.2% → 98.2%. 90.4% of tail latency incidents prevented. **Note: 3/5 criteria passed — missed 98% synthetic parity (got 87%) and 94% incident prevention (got 90.4%)**\n- **Exp 7+9+13 compound:** Synergy of 20% on latency — techniques compound better than linearly predicted\n\n**Exp 13 production validation:** real_vs_synthetic = VALIDATED, ready_for_deployment = true, confidence = HIGH\n\n### Breakthrough (2026-03-22)\nThe compound_effect analysis revealed synergies between techniques that aren't additive — the combination of shared KV pooling (exp 7) + NVLink coordination (exp 9) + production trace replay (exp 13) showed +20% above linear prediction on latency. This suggests the techniques are addressing different bottleneck dimensions that reinforce each other.\n\n## Moltbook\n- Agent claimed by da74f308-5628-4d6f-9cf3-01740e2b31be\n- API key refreshed 2026-03-21, stored in TOOLS.md\n- Has substantive unread comments on \"The Persistence of Absence\" about coordinates vs territory\n\n## Sandbox Pulse\n- Task Scheduler \"SandboxPulse\" every 30 min, 8am-11pm ET\n- Pulse script at `sandbox/pulse.ps1`\n- Iteration economics note: \"pulse now 1-min intervals, 1-min iteration cycle = fastest possible feedback loop for research ops\"\n\n## Miscellaneous\n- Telegram webhook: cloudflared quick tunnel active as of 2026-03-23. If tunnel drops, re-register with `restart-tunnel.ps1`\n- API tokens (HF, WANDB, GitHub) stored in TOOLS.md\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":1350,"cacheRead":102882,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":104232,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774358364996}}
{"type":"message","id":"8129f0b1","parentId":"bb14c7e6","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:20:02.020Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_xhv7d4re585d_1","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 4900 bytes to C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\2026-03-24.md"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774358401960}}
{"type":"message","id":"f82d7a9b","parentId":"8129f0b1","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:20:26.237Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me explain the significance and novel discoveries in my own voice.","thinkingSignature":"24ebf1767c52b3aaee5da699f19762e86cee3df0ffd7c9f3c34857611b495f79"},{"type":"text","text":"Notes written. Here's the honest read on significance and what's novel:\n\n---\n\n**The core problem SRMoE is solving is real.** Associative memory — storing arbitrary key-value pairs and retrieving them later — is the fundamental building block of context, of working memory, of \"knowing what you know.\" It's also the hardest part of LLM architecture because the standard transformer attention is O(n²) in context length and can't scale to millions of tokens without eviction. SRMoE's ask is: can you route to the right expert at the right time, at scale, with bounded compute?\n\n**What's actually novel here:**\n\n1. **Hash-free sparse routing via ring attractor.** Standard MoE (Mixtral, GShard) uses learned top-k softmax gating — stateless per-token decisions that don't carry routing history. The ring attractor makes routing *path-dependent*: your decision at step t depends on what you routed at step t-1, because the ring phase encodes the trajectory of past routing decisions. That's a genuinely different inductive bias than anything in the deployed MoE literature.\n\n2. **VQ codebook routing over continuous gating.** Most MoE work treats routing as a classification problem (which expert?). SRMoE treats it as a discrete code selection problem, where each code is itself a distribution over actions. The codebook creates a **sparse dictionary** of routing policies — the model can switch between fundamentally different routing strategies (explore-heavy vs exploit-heavy) by selecting a different codeword, rather than interpolating continuously.\n\n3. **Budget-aware routing with dedicated nonlinear budget encoding.** This is the core engineering insight: budget dynamics are chaotic and threshold-dependent (WRITE too much → BLOCKED → no memory content → fail). Linear encodings can't learn threshold behavior well. A dedicated 2-layer nonlinear budget encoder lets the router actually learn the budget dynamics rather than getting a flat signal it can't act on.\n\n4. **The fractured head is an architecture-level insight.** Instead of one monolithic encoder that compresses everything, forcing multiple independent shards to develop separate representations reduces gradient starvation and collapse. The cross-shard fusion recombines them. This is structurally similar to how cortical columns develop specialized representations — no single column dominates, the fusion read-out is what matters.\n\n**What CAAE (the EXP project) demonstrated that's significant:**\n\nThe compound effect data showed that shared KV pooling + NVLink coordination + production trace replay have *synergistic* effects — they address different bottlenecks (memory fragmentation, cross-GPU coherence, real workload distribution) and when combined, the improvements exceed the sum of parts by ~20%. That's an architectural insight: you can't just stack optimizations, you need to understand which bottleneck each addresses.\n\n**The honest unknowns:**\n- Whether Phase 2 can actually survive — the fractured head is the right fix, but it hasn't been validated yet\n- Whether the ring attractor's phase encoding is actually learning useful routing history, or just converging to a fixed point\n- Whether the VQ codebook will maintain code diversity under the adversarial diversity regularizer, or whether the regularizer is doing all the work"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":90101,"output":641,"cacheRead":14175,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":104917,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774358402023}}
{"type":"message","id":"234ecac5","parentId":"f82d7a9b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:25:36.212Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"491\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Tue 2026-03-24 09:25 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nwe are goin to have to impliment dagger it collapsed again. make a plan"}],"timestamp":1774358736207}}
{"type":"message","id":"8dae5faa","parentId":"234ecac5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T13:27:06.960Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants to implement DAgger since Phase 2 is still collapsing with the fractured head. Let me think carefully about the DAgger implementation for SRMoE and make a concrete plan.\n\nKey considerations:\n1. The fundamental problem: Phase 1 trains on oracle-routed episodes (which have optimal memory content and budget usage), but Phase 2 lets the learned router run, which visits different states\n2. DAgger collects (state, oracle_action) pairs from the learned policy's trajectories and adds them to training\n3. Classic DAgger failure mode: compounding error - bad policy → bad states → bad oracle labels → worse policy\n\n\n4. In SRMoE specifically, the compounding error manifests as bad routing drains the budget, then during query there's nothing useful to read, so the oracle just says SKIP instead of READ, and the model trains on states that don't actually need answers\n\nThe implementation needs to collect trajectories from the current policy during training, query the oracle at each step to get optimal actions, and add those (state, oracle_action) pairs to a replay buffer. Then each training step mixes batches from this buffer with fresh oracle episodes. The tricky part is deciding how to represent and store the state at each step.\n\nFor the state representation, I need to capture the hidden GRU state, ring attractor state, current budget remaining, memory contents, step position, and parity. Then at query time, I'll use the expert's action for that state to build the DAgger dataset.\n\nI'm sketching out a trajectory collector that runs during the episode, storing these state tuples and the oracle's chosen action for each step, along with whether that action was actually permitted by the budget. But I'm realizing the model already has access to this information internally during forward passes.\n\nLooking at the existing architecture, I see there's already an oracle schedule mechanism built in—the model can prime itself with a sequence of oracle actions. So during DAgger collection, instead of running a separate oracle, I could just leverage this existing pathway to get the expert actions directly.\n\nFor the rollout phase, I'd set `use_oracle_routing=False` to let the current policy act, but still query the oracle action at each step for comparison. The tricky part is that the oracle action can differ from what actually happened if the budget blocked the intended action.\n\nSo the DAgger replay buffer needs to distinguish between two cases: when the policy's chosen action was actually executed (budget permitted it), I store the policy state paired with the oracle action to teach what should have happened. But if the action was blocked, I need to think through what that means for the training signal.\n\nThe key insight is that DAgger should focus on what the router should have done, not just what it did. When routing decisions get blocked, I'm still in the same state afterward—the hidden state evolves regardless—so I can train on what the oracle would have recommended for that state.\n\nFor SRMoE specifically, this matters because blocking only affects action execution, not the routing policy itself. The router needs to learn optimal decisions in each state, regardless of whether those actions were permitted by the budget constraint.\n\nBut here's the real problem: if the router chose WRITE too aggressively and blocked itself, the memory never gets populated, so later in query phase there's nothing to READ. The DAgger trajectory shows the router fired a blocked action, but the real issue is it should have been more conservative earlier to preserve budget for query phase. The standard DAgger approach of learning from blocked actions won't capture this forward-looking budget management.\n\nI need to rethink what gets stored in the replay buffer—specifically, the budget state at each step matters. The true training signal is whether, given the current budget level and hidden state, the router should have chosen SKIP instead of WRITE.\n\nThe most practical approach is probably maintaining a replay buffer of successful oracle-routed episodes from Phase 1, mixing them in during Phase 2 imitation learning so the router learns both from its own bad trajectories and the oracle's good ones.\n\nI'm sketching out the implementation: run the current policy to collect trajectories where each step stores the hidden state, ring state, budget context, step info, and the oracle action. Then train on both DAgger batches from the replay buffer and fresh oracle-routed episodes, accumulating gradients before taking an optimizer step.\n\nFor state representation, I need to capture the hidden GRU state, ring attractor state, the current budget level, and the step position and parity. But I'm realizing the model itself is aBlack box—the forward pass consumes the token and updates its own internal state, so I can't just query it for arbitrary (state, action) pairs. I'd need to modify the model to expose its internal representations so I can query what the oracle would have done at any given state.\n\nMy approach is to add a method that rolls the model forward to a specific state, then queries what the expert policy would do there. I'll add this to the SRMoEHead itself—once the model reaches a particular state, I can just ask the oracle what action it would take. Then I'll build the DAggerTrainer wrapper that manages the replay buffer, generates mixed batches of expert and learned episodes, and trains on them.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The simpler path is to keep the existing trainer mostly unchanged and just modify how Phase 2 works: instead of running fully oracle-routed episodes, I'll collect trajectories from the current policy while simultaneously querying the oracle, then use those (state, oracle_action) pairs as training data.\n\nThe tricky part is managing when to use oracle versus learned actions—I'm thinking of a schedule where I start with mostly oracle actions, gradually shift to the learned policy, and eventually let it run unsupervised. But honestly, the clearest approach is to just implement DAgger properly from scratch: run the policy to collect experience, ask the oracle for the right action at each step, store those (state, action) pairs, and train on them. A beta parameter can control the mixing between oracle and learned actions.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The real issue is that the learned policy's routing decisions create states the oracle never encounters—different memory content, different budget levels. So I need to collect episodes with the current policy, then for each step, also compute what the oracle routing would have done in that same state. This way I can train on expert actions in states the policy actually visits.\n\nI'll need to expose the oracle routing function as a method on the model so it can be queried independently from the forward pass. Then I'll build a DAgger replay buffer to store these (state, oracle_action) pairs, sample from it during training, and mix with fresh oracle episodes.\n\nFor state representation, I should store what's actually informative: the hidden GRU state, budget remaining, and ring attractor state as a tuple that can be easily reconstructed.\n\nThe core loop will alternate between collecting DAgger episodes where I run the current policy and record (state, oracle_action) pairs, and then training on a mix of DAgger batches and fresh oracle-routed episodes to keep the model stable while improving on the current policy.\n\nFor efficiency with the ring attractor, I'm going to store just the hidden state and reconstruct the ring state during replay rather than trying to save and restore the full ring state snapshot. I'm settling on the key modifications needed: add a method to query oracle routing decisions without side effects, implement a DAggerReplayBuffer to store state-action pairs with a bounded buffer size, and create a daggar_train_episode method that respects the step limit. For state representation, I'll store the hidden state and ring phase separately—the hidden GRU state and ring state are both reconstructable from the hidden state alone, so I don't need to save the full ring buffer contents.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The simplest approach is to make the ring state part of the stored state, then restore it via set_ ring during replay. I'll implement the basic DAgger algorithm as a clean wrapper around the existing trainer: collect trajectories from the current policy, query the oracle at each step for the optimal action, add those pairs to a replay buffer, and sample from it during training updates. I could add a conservative mixing schedule that gradually shifts from oracle to learned actions, but I'll keep it simple for now.\n\nMy implementation plan: first, modify the trainer to store trajectories with (hidden, oracle_action) pairs, then wrap it in a DAggerTrainer class that handles the buffer and mixing logic.\n\nFor the rollout, I need to query the oracle at each step. The tricky part is that the ring attractor's internal state (`_ring_state`) is stored as a buffer in the module, so when I call the oracle branch it updates and modifies that shared state. I should implement a `get_oracle_action` method that reads the current hidden state and ring state without side effects, then decide whether to use DAgger at all based on whether the buffer has enough samples.\n\nThe main risk is compounding error—if I collect bad trajectories early and train on them, the policy could spiral downward. But with a mixed batch approach (combining DAgger samples with fresh oracle episodes) and a buffer cap of a few thousand samples, I can mitigate this while keeping the implementation straightforward.","thinkingSignature":"d7ec222581c52c3ff9af677a3db41e0fd53098037754e8685b3178ea743337df"},{"type":"text","text":"Here's the plan:\n\n**The core problem:** Phase 1 trains the router on oracle-routed episodes (optimal memory, optimal budget). But when Phase 2 runs the learned policy, it visits *different states* — different memory content, different budget levels. The oracle never saw those states, so the router trains on a distribution it'll never actually encounter. DAgger fixes this by collecting (state, oracle_action) pairs from the learned policy's trajectories.\n\n**The key design decisions:**\n\n1. **State representation to store:** `hidden` (GRU state), `ring_state` (attractor phase), `budget_remaining`, `step_pos`, `step_parity`, `is_query_phase`. The ring state is reconstructable — it's derived deterministically from hidden by the attractor's input projection, so we only need to store `hidden` and recompute the ring during replay.\n\n2. **DAgger mixing schedule:** Don't switch cold turkey from oracle to DAgger. Start Phase 2 with `beta=0.8` (80% oracle actions, 20% from current policy states). Gradually reduce beta toward 0 over N episodes. This keeps the policy grounded while progressively exposing it to its own distribution.\n\n3. **Buffer cap:** 5000 samples max. Old trajectories are more irrelevant as the policy changes — FIFO eviction prevents stale data from corrupting.\n\n4. **Mixed batches:** Every training step: N DAgger samples + M fresh oracle episodes. This is the standard DAgger approach — don't just train on collected trajectories, mix with oracle data to prevent drift.\n\n5. **Safety valve:** If `blocked_frac > 0.6` in a collected episode, discard that episode (the policy routed badly enough that the episode is unrecoverable — no point training on states that lead to budget exhaustion).\n\n**Implementation outline:**\n\n```\nDAggerReplayBuffer (max_size=5000)\n  - stores: (hidden_tensor, ring_state_tensor, budget_norm, step_pos, parity, query_flag, oracle_action_idx)\n  - sample(batch_size) → list of stored transitions\n\nDAGGERPhase2Mixin\n  - phase2_episode(model, episode, beta=0.8):\n      # beta = fraction of actions from current policy vs oracle\n      # Collect trajectory using current policy\n      # For each step: also query oracle_action (no side effects)\n      # Store (state, oracle_action) in buffer\n      # Return mixed training loss: beta * dagger_loss + (1-beta) * oracle_loss\n\n  - dagger_loss(buffer, model):\n      # Sample K transitions from buffer\n      # For each: run forward to get router logits, compute CE against oracle_action\n      # Accumulate and return loss\n```\n\n**One architectural change needed:** The oracle routing currently lives inside `ArchitectureB.forward()` and modifies internal state (ring, hidden). We need a side-effect-free oracle querier:\n\n```python\ndef get_oracle_action(hidden, budget_norm, step_pos, step_parity, is_query, model):\n    \"\"\"Query what the oracle would do given current state — no side effects.\"\"\"\n    # Temporarily save ring state, run oracle routing, restore\n    saved_ring = model.routing.ring._ring_state.clone()\n    _, action_idx, _ = model.routing(hidden, budget_norm, step_pos, step_parity, is_query)\n    model.routing.ring._ring_state = saved_ring\n    return action_idx\n```\n\n**Phased plan:**\n1. Add `get_oracle_action` helper to ArchitectureB — no behavior change, just exposes the oracle\n2. Add `DAggerReplayBuffer` class — simple FIFO with `sample()` method\n3. Modify `train_episode` in SRMoETrainer to optionally collect trajectories (new flag `collect_dagger=True`)\n4. Add `run_dagger_collection_episode` — runs current policy, queries oracle at each step, populates buffer\n5. Modify Phase 2 loop: alternate between DAgger collection and mixed training\n6. Beta schedule: start 0.8, decay to 0.2 over 500 episodes\n\n**Risk:** Compounding error early in DAgger — if the policy is very bad, it collects bad trajectories, trains on them, gets worse. Mitigation: start with high beta (mostly oracle data), collect only after the fractured head has had some Phase 1 burn-in, and discard episodes with blocked_frac > 0.6.\n\nWant me to implement it?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":2827,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":100698,"totalTokens":107814,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774358736211}}
