phase2_ep == IMITATION_EP:\n 45 print(f' p2 {phase2_ep:5d}: beta={beta:.2f} loss={stats.get(\"mixed_loss\",0):.4f} '\n 46 f'd_l={stats.get(\"dagger_loss\",0):.4f} o_l={stats.get(\"oracle_loss\",0):.4f} '\n 47 f'buf={stats.get(\"buffer_size\",0)} acc={stats.get(\"oracle_acc\",0):.3f}')\n\nCell In[8], line 56, in dagger_train_step(trainer, dagger_buffer, beta, device, collect_stats)\n 53 L_mixed = (1 - beta) * L_dagger + beta * L_oracle\n 55 trainer.opt.zero_grad()\n---> 56 L_mixed.backward()\n 57 torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(trainer.params, 1.0)\n 58 trainer.opt.step()\n\nFile /usr/local/lib/python3.11/dist-packages/torch/_tensor.py:492, in Tensor.backward(self, gradient, retain_graph, create_graph, inputs)\n 482 if has_torch_function_unary(self):\n 483 return handle_torch_function(\n 484 Tensor.backward,\n 485 (self,),\n (...)\n 490 inputs=inputs,\n 491 )\n--> 492 torch.autograd.backward(\n 493 self, gradient, retain_graph, create_graph, inputs=inputs\n 494 )\n\nFile /usr/local/lib/python3.11/dist-packages/torch/autograd/__init__.py:251, in backward(tensors, grad_tensors, retain_graph, create_graph, grad_variables, inputs)\n 246 retain_graph = create_graph\n 248 # The reason we repeat the same comment below is that\n 249 # some Python versions print out the first line of a multi-line function\n 250 # calls in the traceback and some print out the last line\n--> 251 Variable._execution_engine.run_backward( # Calls into the C++ engine to run the backward pass\n 252 tensors,\n 253 grad_tensors_,\n 254 retain_graph,\n 255 create_graph,\n 256 inputs,\n 257 allow_unreachable=True,\n 258 accumulate_grad=True,\n 259 )\n\nRuntimeError: element 0 of tensors does not require grad and does not have a grad_fn"}],"timestamp":1774364031637}}
{"type":"message","id":"1e24ae98","parentId":"fc301a9f","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:55:24.925Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Phase 1 completed successfully in 1761s (~29 minutes) with acc=0.850. Now Phase 2 (DAgger) crashes on the very first `dagger_train_step` call.\n\nThe error:\n```\nRuntimeError: element 0 of tensors does not require grad and does not have a grad_fn\n```\n\nThis means `L_mixed` doesn't require gradients — one of its components (`L_dagger` or `L_oracle`) is detached from the graph, or is a leaf tensor without grad_fn.\n\nLet me look at the `dagger_train_step` function. The issue is in the `dagger_loss_from_buffer` call inside `dagger_train_step`.\n\n\nThe problem is that `dagger_loss_from_buffer` detaches the hidden state when appending to the buffer, so when sampling from the buffer and passing hidden tensors through the router, there's no gradient graph connecting back to the model parameters.\n\nTracing through `dagger_collection_episode`, I see it stores detached hidden states in the buffer, which should be fine. But then in `dagger_loss_from_buffer`, when sampling from the buffer and calling `dagger_train_step` with those stored hiddens, the forward pass through the router doesn't build a gradient graph because the inputs were detached at storage time.\n\nLooking at the actual forward pass in `dagger_train_step`, each step calls `m.routing(...)` with a hidden vector from the buffer. The model is in `.eval()` mode by default, which disables dropout but shouldn't affect whether gradients are computed.\n\nThe real issue is that `L_dagger` is coming back as a Python float wrapped in a tensor, not an actual computation graph. When `dagger_loss_from_buffer` returns `torch.tensor(0.0, device=device)`, it creates a leaf tensor without grad_fn, so when we try to do `(1 - beta) * L_dagger`, there's no gradient to backpropagate.\n\nI need to check the actual implementation of `dagger_loss_from_buffer` to see what's happening with the loss computation and whether the buffer sampling is properly detaching the computation graph. The routing is set to evaluation mode with `set_eval_mode(True)`, which means it uses hard argmax instead of the Gumbel-softmax branch. But that shouldn't affect the gradient computation—the routing head's parameters still have `requires_grad=True` even when in eval mode.\n\nThe actual issue is likely in how the hidden states are being passed to the loss function. If `hiddens[i]` was already detached before entering `dagger_loss_from_buffer`, then even though the router parameters have gradients enabled, there's no computational graph connecting back to those parameters from that particular hidden tensor.\n\nThe real culprit is probably the batch normalization or dropout layers. When the model switches to eval mode, these layers behave differently—batch norm uses running statistics instead of batch statistics, and dropout is disabled. But more importantly, when running the router on detached hidden states, if the first linear layer uses `bias` as a parameter, that would create a computation that flows through `bias`, which should have gradients enabled.\n\nActually, I think the issue is simpler: the routing module is in eval mode, which might be affecting how the gradients flow back through the network. Let me trace through the actual computation to see where the gradient computation breaks down.\n\nWhen `m.routing(h, ...)` is called on a detached hidden vector, the parameters still have `requires_grad=True` since they're part of the model, so the computation graph should be built correctly. But then when computing the loss and calling `.backward()`, if `m.routing` has batch norm layers in eval mode, the running mean/variance are used instead of the batch statistics, which shouldn't prevent gradients from flowing through the parameters themselves.\n\nThe real issue might be that the loss is being computed as a Python float from `L_dagger.item()` somewhere, but the backprop should still work through the tensor operations. Let me reconsider the architecture to see if there's a parameter without `requires_grad=True` that's being used in the computation path. I need to force `m.routing` into train mode since eval mode might be affecting how batch norm or dropout behave during the gradient computation. When `dagger_collection_episode` calls `model.eval()`, that applies to the entire model, but `dagger_train_step` doesn't explicitly switch it back to train mode before computing the loss. The routing parameters should still have `requires_grad=True` since they're in an `Adam` optimizer, but the training/eval mode difference could be interfering with gradient flow through the loss computation. I need to verify whether `dagger_train_step` actually switches to training mode before computing the loss. Looking at the implementation, I see it calculates the dagger loss and oracle loss separately, then mixes them together and calls `backward()` — but I'm not seeing the model switched to train mode before that backward call happens.\n\nActually, that shouldn't matter for autograd since the parameters retain their `requires_grad` regardless of the model's mode. Let me trace through the buffer implementation to see if there's a tensor operation issue there.\n\nI'm wondering if the problem is in how `dagger_loss_from_buffer` handles the hidden state. When `dagger_train_step` calls it with `model` and then passes `model.routing` to the loss function, the hidden tensors come from a buffer that was populated during collection. Let me check what `dagger_collection_episode` actually stored in that buffer.\n\nDuring collection, the model runs in eval mode with `torch.no_grad()`, so the hidden states it saves are already detached from any computation graph. When I sample from the buffer and pass these detached tensors into the routing function, the parameters still have `requires_grad=True`, so the forward pass should build a computation graph connecting them to the output logits. Then calling backward on the loss should propagate gradients through those parameters.\n\nThe issue might be that `dagger_collection_episode` is in eval mode, which could be affecting how the model's parameters behave during the forward pass, even though they're not in `no_grad` mode themselves. Let me reconsider whether the routing module's behavior changes in eval mode in a way that breaks gradient tracking.\n\nActually, I think the real problem could be with how batched tensor operations interact with autograd when processing multiple samples. If `hiddens` is a stacked tensor and I'm iterating through it, the way gradients flow back through the batched computation might not work as expected. Or there could be a detach happening somewhere in the forward pass that's breaking the computation graph before backward is even called.\n\nLooking more carefully at the `dagger_loss_from_buffer` implementation, I'm wondering if there's a mismatch between what the training loop is passing and what the function expects. The error message is pretty specific though—\"element 0 of tensors does not require grad and does not have a grad_fn\"—which suggests that when `L_mixed` tries to compute gradients, one of its component tensors isn't connected to the computation graph at all.\n\nLet me trace through the training step logic again. The `dagger_train_step` function samples from the buffer and computes both a dagger loss and an oracle loss, then mixes them together with the beta weighting. The issue is likely that one of these losses isn't properly connected to the model's parameters when the backward pass runs. I should check whether the buffer is storing the hidden states as leaf tensors or if something is detaching them along the way. the routing module returns `action_logits` which should have `grad_fn` from the linear layer computation, and then `F.cross_entropy` on that should also produce a tensor with `grad_fn`. So `total_loss` should be accumulating gradients properly. But then I need to trace through what happens when `L_mixed` tries to backward — if `L_dagger` is coming back as a tensor with `grad_fn` from the buffer loss computation, and the weights applied to it are just scalars, the backward should flow through correctly. Unless there's something about how `dagger_train_step` is mixing the losses or computing the final loss that's breaking the gradient flow.\n\nThe real issue might be that somewhere in the training loop, `trainer.model` gets switched to eval mode or its parameters get `requires_grad=False` set, which would break backpropagation entirely.\n\nLet me reconsider whether `dagger_train_step` is actually putting the model in training mode before calling `dagger_loss_from_buffer`. If it isn't, that could explain why the gradients aren't flowing through properly.\n\nLooking at the `dagger_train_step` function, it seems like it's computing losses but not explicitly setting the model to train mode. This means the model is still in eval mode when computing the dagger loss, which uses the router's parameters that require gradients.\n\nEven in eval mode, those parameters should have `requires_grad=True` since they're part of the optimizer, so the computation graph should still build. But maybe there's something about how the forward pass works in eval mode that's preventing the gradients from being computed correctly.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be simpler - the model is shared between the dagger trainer and the oracle trainer, so when one sets it to eval mode, it affects the other. And in `dagger_train_step`, even though we're calling `backward()` on the loss, something about how the losses are being mixed or computed might be preventing the gradients from flowing back to the router's parameters. `dagger_loss_from_buffer` takes the same `model` object as the trainer. The trainer's optimizer includes the routing parameters. So when we call `dagger_loss_from_buffer(model, ...)`, and the routing forward pass computes gradients w.r.t. those parameters, `L_dagger.backward()` should accumulate gradients into `trainer.opt`.\n\nUnless `dagger_loss_from_buffer` somehow detaches the computation. Let me re-read it carefully:\n\nThe function samples a batch, and for each sample it retrieves the hidden state and then calls `model.routing(...)`. The hidden state from the buffer is detached from the graph. The routing forward pass computes action logits and cross-entropy loss against the oracle action, accumulating into `total_loss`. Since `model.routing` contains parameters with `requires_grad=True`, `total_loss.backward()` should properly propagate gradients back through the routing module.\n\nBut here's what I'm noticing: `L_dagger` is computed as `total_loss / max(n, 1)`. For a single sample, this is just `step_loss / 1`. The backward should flow through fine. I need to check if there's a `.item()` call somewhere that's breaking the computation graph, but looking at the code, I don't see one. The issue might be something else entirely.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the error message: \"element 0 of tensors does not require grad and does not have a grad_fn\". This suggests one of the tensors in the list passed to `backward()` is a leaf tensor without gradients. In `dagger_train_step`, the tensors being passed are `L_dagger` and `L_oracle`, and I need to figure out which one is the problem.\n\nWait, I think I see it now. When `dagger_loss_from_buffer` returns `torch.tensor(0.0, device=device)` for an empty buffer, that's a leaf tensor with no `grad_fn`. When we compute `L_mixed = (1 - beta) * L_dagger + beta * L_oracle`, if the buffer is empty and `L_dagger` is that leaf tensor, then calling `.backward()` on `L_mixed` will fail because it contains a component that doesn't require gradients.\n\nBut that doesn't make sense because if the buffer is empty, `dagger_loss_from_buffer` should return early and we'd get `L_oracle` from the fresh oracle episodes instead. Unless both losses end up as these leaf tensors somehow.\n\nLooking at the buffer sampling logic, if `len(self.buffer) == 0`, we return `torch.tensor(0.0, device=device)`. This creates a leaf tensor with no gradient history. The real issue is probably that when we compute the mixed loss and call `.backward()`, we're trying to backpropagate through a computation that includes this empty-buffer result, which doesn't have the necessary gradient information.\n\nActually, I think the culprit might be simpler - the model itself might not be in training mode. When `dagger_train_step` is called, it never sets `model.train()`, so if the model was left in eval mode from a previous call, certain operations like batch normalization or dropout could be behaving differently and breaking the gradient computation.\n\nBut that shouldn't affect parameter gradients in eval mode... unless there's something with `F.gumbel_softmax` in the routing head. Let me trace through the `forward` pass again - when `self._eval_mode` is True and `tau <= 0`, it uses argmax selection, and the `action_logits` are reconstructed from the selected codebook entry, which should still allow gradients to flow through the codebook parameters.\n\nI'm hitting a wall here - the issue might be in how `dagger_train_step` itself is structured. The function computes `L_dagger` and `L_oracle`, mixes them together, and calls `backward()`, but I'm not seeing where the gradient computation is actually breaking down.\n\nThe problem could be that `dagger_train_step` is being invoked from within a `model.eval()` context in the Phase 2 loop, which would prevent gradient tracking. But even in eval mode, autograd should still work for the forward pass - the model itself is in eval mode, not disabled globally.\n\nI think I need to just try adding `model.train()` at the start of `dagger_train_step` and see if that resolves the issue. Looking back at the `dagger_train_step` function, it starts with computing `L_dagger` from the buffer using the model in its current state, which might be the culprit.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there could be a parameter sharing issue - if `dagger_train_step` is being called when the model is still in eval mode from `dagger_collection_episode`, that might be preventing gradients from flowing correctly through the computation.\n\nBut wait, eval mode shouldn't actually break autograd - it just affects things like dropout and batch norm behavior. The parameters themselves should still be trainable.\n\nLet me try a different angle: when I call `dagger_loss_from_buffer` and compute gradients, I need to make sure the model is actually in training mode so the gradients flow properly through all the layers. I think the issue might be that the optimizer's parameters are the same objects as the model's parameters, so as long as we're not somehow detaching them, the gradients should accumulate correctly. Let me try adding `model.train()` at the start of `dagger_train_step` to ensure dropout behaves correctly, since that could be interfering with the gradient flow. I should also check whether the parameters actually have `requires_grad=True` set before attempting the backward pass.","thinkingSignature":"413ada0c0fed09b82e98ecf1a42b43ab52b9ec816bf9dc20852f161ebd03a13d"},{"type":"text","text":"Phase 1 clean — `blocked_frac=0` throughout. Phase 2 crashes immediately. The error is clear: `L_mixed` has a component that doesn't require gradients. Let me check the function:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e10lu8gfp24g_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python -c \"\nimport json\nwith open(r'C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb', 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f: nb = json.load(f)\nsrc = ''.join(nb['cells'][8]['source'])\nlines = src.split(chr(10))\nfor i, l in enumerate(lines):\n    if 'def dagger_train_step' in l or 'L_mixed' in l or 'backward' in l or 'dagger_loss' in l:\n        print('%3d: %s' % (i, repr(l)[:80]))\n\""}}],"api":"anthr